===DESAMBIGUATION==

Portmanteau comes from the French words porter and manteau.  It is simply an anglicism introduced into the English language in the past 5 years with different meaning from different sources.  Porter (in French) means to hold.  Manteaux are jackets, winter coats and any other coats.  As for porte-manteau, also called in French “patère” it is simply a coat rack use to hang coats without a hanger that holds on a tripod as demonstrated at http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porte-manteau  Portmanteau is not “the combination of any two words” such as Enbridge (Energy Bridge) this is an acronym.  Acronym is often associated with initialism which is a word created by the first letter from many words such as IBM (Int’l Business Machines).  At last, there are abbreviations such as “modem” (modulate, demodulate) or codec (coding, decoding).  Porte-manteau has also been used for small luggage needed for a short travel with basic clothing as we could compare it to carry-on luggage on an aircraft or train.  Porte-manteau was mainly used by French Canadians before the 80's being replaced by “patère” as porte-manteau is an expression from the “old French” from the 1700's.  A morpheme is the use of an existing word with either a prefix or suffix such as the word happiness, though the word "happy" does exist on its own but "ness" is noting else than a suffix. Porte-manteau has been in use since 1759 in French.

